article.headline: Houston's 10-0 second-half run breaks it open
article.linkText: Thompson leads Comets' eclipse of the Sun
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Tina Thompson and the Houston Comets are starting
to put things together.

Thompson scored 18 points to lead Houston to a 72-56 victory
over the Connecticut Sun on Saturday night, the first time in more
than a month that the Comets have won consecutive games.

"Right now we are being a little more patient," Thompson said.
"I think before we were getting shots, but we weren't patient
enough. But right now we are making their defense work a lot more
and were getting great shots and making them."

After Taj McWilliams-Franklin's layup pulled the Sun to 41-40
early in the second half, Houston (10-12) responded with a
10-0 run to break the game open.

Thompson and Sheryl Swoopes (15 points) each scored four points
during the run for the Comets, who hadn't won consecutive games
since mid-June.

Michelle Snow scored 10 points and Sheila Lambert added a
career-high nine assists for the Comets.

"My main focus when I'm out there is to worry about how I'm
going to get my team going," Lambert said. "I like to shoot, but
when someone else is hot, I have to get them the ball to give us
the best chance to score."

Nykesha Sales scored 19 points for the Sun (11-11), who have
lost three straight and four of five following a six-game winning
streak. Connecticut was outscored 31-18 in the second half and made
just five of their final 28 shots.

"It was a little bit of everything tonight," Connecticut coach
Mike Thibault said. "Their good defense and our bad shooting
didn't help, but they were good defensively.

"Basketball is a real simple game. It either goes in or it
doesn't go in. Tonight, their shots went in and ours didn't," he
said.

Sales attempted just four shots -- making one -- in the second
half and Asjha Jones was the only Sun player to make more than one
field goal in the second half.

"When most of the team is struggling on offense, it is hard to
put points on the board," Sales said. "They started hitting a lot
of shots in transition, and that is what hurt us tonight."

The Comets had a 41-38 lead at halftime despite losing Swoopes,
who re-aggravated a sprained right ankle in the eighth minute of
the game. She was treated during the intermission and returned to
score six points in 14 second-half minutes.

Swoopes did not play in Houston's 97-61 win over Detroit on
Thursday night.

"It's kind of frustrating for me right now because it is a
day-to-day thing," Swoopes said. "Am I going to play? And if I
do, for how long? I think that just adds frustration to my
teammates. They don'tt know if I'm in or out or what the deal is.
Right now it is still very sore, very stiff."

The Sun built a 9-1 lead in the first 2:17, but the Comets
responded with an 18-2 spurt over the next 5:42.
